6-03-11T09:13:03.155Z","id":"cmmltmsab0000qpxzsseydg4s","summary":"The \"Secret History of the Mongols\" recounts the origin of the Mongol lineage starting with Börte Chino and Goo Maral, who settled on Mount Burkhan Khaldun and had Batachikhan. The genealogy continues through several generations to Dobu Mergen and his wife Alun-gua. After Dobu Mergen's death, Alun-gua famously bore three more sons, including Bodonchar Munkhag, from whom the Borjigin clan originated. She attributed their conception not to a servant, but to a \"white-yellow man from the sky.\"\n\nFrom Bodonchar Munkhag's line also came the ancestors of Jamukha (Genghis Khan's sworn brother) and the Taijuud clan (from Khaidu). The direct lineage to Genghis Khan continued through Tumbinai Setsen to Khabul Khan, who ruled the Khamag Mongol and founded the Khiad Borjigin clan. Khabul Khan's second son, Bartan Baatar, was the grandfather of Genghis Khan, making Yesukhei Baatar (Genghis Khan's father) a prominent leader of the Khiad Borjigin. Many influential nobles involved in Genghis Khan's state-building were Khiad Borjigin lords and his relatives, descendants of Khabul Khan.","title":"f","updatedAt":"2026-03-11T09:13:03.155Z","userId":"cmmlgsozn0000ryxzhencb9ob"},"message":"Article created","success":true}
